00:03:48.840 --> 00:03:50.250
Some philosophers have said

00:03:50.250 --> 00:03:53.610
that the meaning of an
artwork is part of it

00:03:53.610 --> 00:03:56.970
albeit not a part that
you can see with your eyes.

00:03:56.970 --> 00:03:59.250
Take for instance, "Fountain",

00:03:59.250 --> 00:04:01.920
one of the most famous works of art ever.

00:04:01.920 --> 00:04:04.890
It was presented in 1917 by Marcel Duchamp

00:04:04.890 --> 00:04:07.080
and it's what's called a readymade,

00:04:07.080 --> 00:04:09.750
a sculpture that was already made

00:04:09.750 --> 00:04:12.900
because it's just an ordinary urinal.

00:04:12.900 --> 00:04:14.700
He bought it from a shop.

00:04:14.700 --> 00:04:17.130
To the eyes, "Fountain" is identical

00:04:17.130 --> 00:04:19.830
to other urinals that are not art.

00:04:19.830 --> 00:04:21.303
So, the argument goes,

00:04:21.303 --> 00:04:24.990
what makes it different is its meaning.

00:04:24.990 --> 00:04:28.110
If you don't get that
meaning, you have in a sense

00:04:28.110 --> 00:04:31.860
failed to experience the
artwork that is "Fountain".

00:04:31.860 --> 00:04:33.600
You've just seen a urinal.

00:04:33.600 --> 00:04:37.500
Funnily enough, I have
some artwork with me today

00:04:37.500 --> 00:04:41.730
that is about this very
question. (Interpreting art,

00:04:41.730 --> 00:04:43.500
not whether your friend
is flirting with you.)

00:04:43.500 --> 00:04:45.780
Although actually kind of both!

00:04:45.780 --> 00:04:49.410
This is "Pale Fire" by Vladimir Nabokov.

00:04:49.410 --> 00:04:52.500
One of the most famous
novels of the 20th century.

00:04:52.500 --> 00:04:57.500
The story is that the poet,
John Shade, has been murdered

00:04:57.960 --> 00:05:01.650
on the night that he
completed his greatest work.

00:05:01.650 --> 00:05:04.650
So the poem has been
published posthumously

00:05:04.650 --> 00:05:06.750
by his good friend, Charles,

00:05:06.750 --> 00:05:10.380
with notes explaining its meaning.

00:05:10.380 --> 00:05:15.380
But as we read on, Charles'
notes get weirder and weirder.

00:05:16.200 --> 00:05:18.930
He starts claiming that
certain words in the poem

00:05:18.930 --> 00:05:20.430
are really a coded message

00:05:20.430 --> 00:05:21.930
about how John was in love with him

00:05:21.930 --> 00:05:23.490
but his wife wouldn't let him say it,

00:05:23.490 --> 00:05:26.520
and really, the poem is all about Charles,

00:05:26.520 --> 00:05:27.960
until he's talking about things

00:05:27.960 --> 00:05:30.120
that are completely unconnected

00:05:30.120 --> 00:05:34.890
and we're like, "Hang on a
minute... did he murder John?!"

00:05:34.890 --> 00:05:37.230
A lot of the humour comes from the fact

00:05:37.230 --> 00:05:41.040
that Charles' interpretation
of the poem is wrong.

00:05:41.040 --> 00:05:44.675
He says it's about one thing, it obviously isn't, 
and that's why it's funny,

00:05:44.675 --> 00:05:47.794
but how do we know he's wrong?

00:05:47.794 --> 00:05:53.070
Well, it would be very helpful if we could just ask John
what his poem is about.

00:05:53.070 --> 00:05:55.170
And indeed, some philosophers have said,

00:05:55.170 --> 00:05:57.450
the way you find out an artwork's meaning

00:05:57.450 --> 00:06:00.810
is you look at the artist's intention.

00:06:00.810 --> 00:06:02.700
If it seems like your
friend is flirting with you

00:06:02.700 --> 00:06:06.420
but it's kind of ambiguous,
just ask her how she feels!

00:06:06.420 --> 00:06:08.760
But it doesn't really
help us with "Pale Fire"

00:06:08.760 --> 00:06:09.840
because the whole setup

00:06:09.840 --> 00:06:12.330
is that John Shade has been murdered.

00:06:12.330 --> 00:06:13.950
We don't know what he intended.

00:06:13.950 --> 00:06:17.760
Maybe Charles is right and
the poem really is about him.

00:06:17.760 --> 00:06:20.400
And this problem comes
up a lot in art history.

00:06:20.400 --> 00:06:23.440
We have evidence of what
artists like Rothko and Duchamp

00:06:24.324 --> 00:06:26.460
intended for their works, but
often that isn't the case,

00:06:26.460 --> 00:06:28.710
especially if the art is very old.

00:06:28.710 --> 00:06:30.990
And even if we could go back

00:06:30.990 --> 00:06:33.930
and reconstruct an artist's intention,

00:06:33.930 --> 00:06:36.060
it might not be a very secure foundation

00:06:36.060 --> 00:06:39.060
on which to base an
interpretation of their work.

00:06:39.060 --> 00:06:40.980
The French philosopher Michel Foucault

00:06:40.980 --> 00:06:43.297
pointed out that the author of a text

00:06:43.297 --> 00:06:47.520
is sometimes a bit of a vague
construct, even a brand.

00:06:47.520 --> 00:06:50.040
Basically, our reconstruction

00:06:50.040 --> 00:06:52.770
would kindof be an
interpretation as well.

00:06:52.770 --> 00:06:55.590
As Charles shows us,
it's perfectly possible

00:06:55.590 --> 00:06:59.010
to imagine an idea of
somebody in your head

00:06:59.010 --> 00:07:01.620
who supports your
interpretation of their work,

00:07:01.620 --> 00:07:04.350
but who isn't that
close to the real thing.

00:07:04.350 --> 00:07:06.649
Maybe your friend is flirting with you,

00:07:06.649 --> 00:07:09.540
but maybe you're just projecting

00:07:09.540 --> 00:07:13.712
because secretly, you kindof want her to.

