00:07:17.370 --> 00:07:20.880
The risk is that we just end
up repeating what other people

00:07:20.880 --> 00:07:23.430
have told us about the
artists' intentions,

00:07:23.430 --> 00:07:25.350
regurgitating the marketing

00:07:25.350 --> 00:07:28.350
rather than actually engaging
with what they've made.

00:07:28.350 --> 00:07:30.757
That's why the philosopher
Roland Barthes said

00:07:30.757 --> 00:07:32.640
we should forget about the author

00:07:32.640 --> 00:07:34.590
and just focus on the text

00:07:34.590 --> 00:07:39.270
In his famous essay, "Death
of the Author", which yeah,

00:07:39.270 --> 00:07:42.020
John is dead, so I guess you
got what you wanted there.

00:07:44.970 --> 00:07:46.440
Roland Barthes, where were you

00:07:46.440 --> 00:07:48.690
on the night that John Shade was murdered?

00:07:48.690 --> 00:07:51.600
Just to make things even more hazy,

00:07:51.600 --> 00:07:54.065
the British artist
historian Michael Baxandall

00:07:54.065 --> 00:07:56.280
said that artists don't really have

00:07:56.280 --> 00:08:00.420
intentions for their work the
same way that an architect

00:08:00.420 --> 00:08:02.250
has an intention for a bridge.

00:08:02.250 --> 00:08:03.660
When you design a bridge,

00:08:03.660 --> 00:08:05.580
you plan it all out beforehand

00:08:05.580 --> 00:08:08.130
and you have a very clear goal in mind,

00:08:08.130 --> 00:08:11.010
but art doesn't really work that way.

00:08:11.010 --> 00:08:13.410
Every brushstroke you add to a canvas,

00:08:13.410 --> 00:08:16.980
every line to a script,
every note to a score,

00:08:16.980 --> 00:08:20.730
changes the relationships
between everything else

00:08:20.730 --> 00:08:22.630
and changes the whole.

00:08:22.630 --> 00:08:26.700
As you work, your intention develops.

00:08:26.700 --> 00:08:29.687
So if we're trying to reconstruct
the artist's intention,

00:08:29.687 --> 00:08:31.290
where do we start?

00:08:31.290 --> 00:08:32.940
There isn't really one intention.

00:08:32.940 --> 00:08:35.340
There's an infinite sequence of them.

00:08:35.340 --> 00:08:38.250
John Singer Sergeant
took almost a whole year

00:08:38.250 --> 00:08:40.290
to finish "The Portrait of Madame X,"

00:08:40.290 --> 00:08:41.749
and he tried a lot of different poses

00:08:41.749 --> 00:08:44.133
before he settled on the final thing.

00:08:45.390 --> 00:08:48.000
Rothko took years to
finish the Seagram murals

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:48.990
and he changed his mind

00:08:48.990 --> 00:08:50.550
about what he wanted to do with them.

00:08:50.550 --> 00:08:52.470
As somebody who is a working artist,

00:08:52.470 --> 00:08:53.730
I can tell you from experience

00:08:53.730 --> 00:08:55.920
that intentions absolutely change.

00:08:55.920 --> 00:08:59.040
I recently finished writing a play.

00:08:59.040 --> 00:09:02.130
It's gonna be on in London
soon. It's called "The Prince".

00:09:02.130 --> 00:09:03.750
I'm really, really excited for it!

00:09:03.750 --> 00:09:06.270
Tickets available in the doobleydoo
if you're interested!

00:09:06.270 --> 00:09:09.570
When I started it I
intended to write something

00:09:09.570 --> 00:09:11.970
about the monarchy, but the more I worked

00:09:11.970 --> 00:09:13.320
the more I realised it actually needed

00:09:13.320 --> 00:09:14.760
to be about something
completely different,

00:09:14.760 --> 00:09:17.310
and the final product has
almost nothing to do with that.

00:09:17.310 --> 00:09:20.430
So if we try to reconstruct
my original intention

00:09:20.430 --> 00:09:24.420
to decide what the play is
about, how is that gonna work?

00:09:24.420 --> 00:09:28.680
It definitely seems like
you can be wrong about art,

00:09:28.680 --> 00:09:30.000
but I'm still not clear

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:32.433
on how you can make sure you're right.

00:09:33.750 --> 00:09:36.602
I am "The Portrait of Madame
X" by John Singer Sergeant,

00:09:36.602 --> 00:09:38.854
am I a study in light and shade?

00:09:38.854 --> 00:09:41.490
Or am I a sexual scandal?

00:09:41.490 --> 00:09:43.087
