00:13:35.850 --> 00:13:40.263
The whole thing was actually consensual 
and she's just lying to get his money.

00:13:41.940 --> 00:13:44.145
The slimiest possible thing!

00:13:44.145 --> 00:13:46.940
But as the play goes on,

00:13:47.880 --> 00:13:49.710
it starts to emerge

00:13:49.710 --> 00:13:53.610
that maybe that really
is what's happening.

00:13:53.610 --> 00:13:57.390
Maybe there really is some
kind of reverse racism,

00:13:57.390 --> 00:14:00.960
reverse Me Too thing happening here.

00:14:00.960 --> 00:14:03.690
And Mamet loves to write
these kinds of stories.

00:14:03.690 --> 00:14:05.280
He did another play called "Oleanna",

00:14:05.280 --> 00:14:07.500
which is about a female
student who falsely accuses

00:14:07.500 --> 00:14:09.450
her professor of sexually assaulting her.

00:14:09.450 --> 00:14:12.660
But then... he really does!

00:14:12.660 --> 00:14:16.440
He loves to write these Tim
Pool-ass thought experiments.

00:14:16.440 --> 00:14:18.930
If you tried to take "Race"

00:14:18.930 --> 00:14:23.250
and translate it into
a political statement,

00:14:23.250 --> 00:14:24.930
the statement that you get

00:14:24.930 --> 00:14:28.260
would probably be a little bit incoherent.

00:14:28.260 --> 00:14:30.540
And I'm not just saying that
because I personally disagree

00:14:30.540 --> 00:14:31.740
with Mamet's politics.

00:14:31.740 --> 00:14:33.870
In his book "Theater",

00:14:33.870 --> 00:14:36.450
he occasionally talks
about his political views

00:14:36.450 --> 00:14:40.800
and it contradicts itself
from chapter to chapter.

00:14:40.800 --> 00:14:43.380
The stuff about theatre
is really interesting.

00:14:43.380 --> 00:14:46.200
The stuff about politics kind of reads

00:14:46.200 --> 00:14:49.830
a little bit like discount
Jordan Peterson, and fair enough!

00:14:49.830 --> 00:14:52.140
Man's a playwright, not
a political scientist!

00:14:52.140 --> 00:14:57.131
But I saw "Race" on Broadway in 2010

00:14:57.131 --> 00:15:00.360
and it was electric.

00:15:00.360 --> 00:15:02.820
The performance was so good

00:15:02.820 --> 00:15:04.830
that when I came out of the
theater, I was like, "That's it,

00:15:04.830 --> 00:15:07.470
I have to be an actress." And years later,

00:15:07.470 --> 00:15:09.390
I did a monologue from "Race"

00:15:09.390 --> 00:15:13.260
at my drama school
auditions, and I got in.

00:15:13.260 --> 00:15:16.293
Mamet says that if you are writing a play,

00:15:17.389 --> 00:15:20.460
creating a work of art for the
stage, forget about politics,

00:15:20.460 --> 00:15:23.370
forget about interpretations
and meaning and getting it

00:15:23.370 --> 00:15:26.970
and all of that [jackoff noises]
Is it entertaining?

00:15:26.970 --> 00:15:28.980
Do the audience wanna
know what happens next?

00:15:28.980 --> 00:15:30.270
If you're singing in
front of a work of art

00:15:30.270 --> 00:15:32.430
and you're trying to get
it, then you're a fool.

00:15:32.430 --> 00:15:35.748
The play, the story, that's
the thing that we're here for.

00:15:35.748 --> 00:15:38.520
As somebody who's just
finished writing a play

00:15:38.520 --> 00:15:41.310
and is going to be in it
soon, there have been times

00:15:41.310 --> 00:15:43.860
where I've found that to
be really useful advice.

00:15:43.860 --> 00:15:46.620
In fairness, I'm white,
so when I watch "Race,"

00:15:46.620 --> 00:15:48.210
I can turn off the bit of my brain

00:15:48.210 --> 00:15:49.800
that worries about the politics stuff.

00:15:49.800 --> 00:15:51.630
Maybe someday David
Mamet will write a play

00:15:51.630 --> 00:15:53.520
about trans people and
I won't have the luxury

00:15:53.520 --> 00:15:54.960
of being entertained anymore,

00:15:54.960 --> 00:15:57.450
but for now, let's take
this idea and run with it.

00:15:57.450 --> 00:15:59.790
Forget about trying to interpret the art.

00:15:59.790 --> 00:16:01.923
Just... how do you feel?

00:16:04.080 --> 00:16:06.547
When I look at Rothko, I feel... uh...

00:16:10.380 --> 00:16:12.300
It's big, it's black, it's maroon, it's red.

00:16:12.300 --> 00:16:13.120
It's, uh...

00:16:17.675 --> 00:16:18.792
I feel humbled.

00:16:19.110 --> 00:16:25.247
I feel in awe, I feel sad.

00:16:27.240 --> 00:16:31.320
You know that feeling
where something bad happens,

00:16:31.320 --> 00:16:34.110
but you kind of knew it was going to,

00:16:34.110 --> 00:16:37.620
like when somebody tells you
they don't love you anymore

00:16:37.620 --> 00:16:39.750
and you kind of saw it coming,

00:16:39.750 --> 00:16:44.010
or you're at a funeral
and the person's died,

00:16:44.010 --> 00:16:45.263
but they've been ill
for a really long time.

00:16:45.263 --> 00:16:56.004
And it's like, well, it's sad,
but at least it's done now.

00:16:56.004 --> 00:16:58.533
That's kind of how Rothko makes me feel.

00:17:00.120 --> 00:17:04.170
Or at least that is part of it.

00:17:04.170 --> 00:17:06.633
But there might be a
bit of a problem here.

00:17:07.680 --> 00:17:11.400
Truth be told, whenever
I'm in an art gallery,

00:17:11.400 --> 00:17:13.918
I always feel low key anxious

00:17:13.918 --> 00:17:17.502
because I used to date an art historian.

00:17:17.502 --> 00:17:20.310
And we would sometimes
go to galleries together.

00:17:20.310 --> 00:17:23.220
We're talking ancient history
now, years and years ago,

00:17:23.220 --> 00:17:25.200
but that relationship ended pretty badly

00:17:25.200 --> 00:17:27.420
for reasons that were my fault.

00:17:27.420 --> 00:17:29.610
So now whenever I'm in an art gallery,

00:17:29.610 --> 00:17:33.243
I'm always like, "What if she's here?"

00:17:34.153 --> 00:17:37.020
[Kim Petras' "Reminds Me" plays]

00:17:37.020 --> 00:17:40.410
My point is, people
feel all sorts of things

00:17:40.410 --> 00:17:41.510
when they look at art.

00:17:42.507 --> 00:17:44.070
Sometimes I look at Rothko and
I feel anxious about my ex.

00:17:44.070 --> 00:17:45.240
Sometimes I look at Rothko

00:17:45.240 --> 00:17:48.210
and I feel like suddenly I have to pee.

00:17:48.210 --> 00:17:51.903
So which feelings are the right ones?

00:17:52.890 --> 00:17:55.890
Even if I'm just focusing
on my emotional reactions,

00:17:55.890 --> 00:17:57.540
how do I know that I've got it?

00:17:57.540 --> 00:18:00.780
We can probably narrow
it down a little bit.

00:18:00.780 --> 00:18:03.797
Like we could say that your
feelings should be caused

00:18:03.797 --> 00:18:06.870
by the particular artwork
you're looking at.

00:18:06.870 --> 00:18:09.750
Yes, I might look at Rothko
and feel anxious about my ex,

00:18:09.750 --> 00:18:11.940
but that's not caused by Rothko.

00:18:11.940 --> 00:18:14.640
Any painting in any gallery would do that.

00:18:14.640 --> 00:18:16.800
I might look at it and feel
that I have to pee, but again,

00:18:16.800 --> 00:18:19.920
that's not caused by the
Rothko, that's just coincidence.

00:18:19.920 --> 00:18:24.090
But even then, that might not be enough.

00:18:24.090 --> 00:18:26.220
Whenever I look at the Seagram murals,

00:18:26.220 --> 00:18:28.407
I think about "Spider-Man 2."

00:18:29.280 --> 00:18:32.190
The story of how Rothko made
them was adapted into a play

00:18:32.190 --> 00:18:34.350
called "Red", which starred Alfred Molina,

00:18:34.350 --> 00:18:36.510
who played Dr. Octopus
in "Spider-Man 2".

00:18:36.510 --> 00:18:38.850
I really liked Alfred
Molina's performance in "Red".

00:18:38.850 --> 00:18:42.660
So now whenever I look at
those particular paintings,

00:18:42.660 --> 00:18:44.820
there's a part of me that feels happy, 'cause I'm like,

00:18:44.820 --> 00:18:48.570
"Oh yeah... Alfred Molina!"

00:18:48.570 --> 00:18:50.940
- There's a huge amount of input

00:18:50.940 --> 00:18:52.950
and a whole new vibe really.

00:18:52.950 --> 00:18:57.390
- My feelings are caused
by that specific painting

00:18:57.390 --> 00:19:01.770
and they don't seem
relevant to its meaning,

00:19:01.770 --> 00:19:04.860
but then we are right
back where we started!

00:19:04.860 --> 00:19:09.071
It really seems like the
artwork has a correct meaning

00:19:09.071 --> 00:19:12.180
that determines whether or not I get it.

00:19:12.180 --> 00:19:16.560
And you might be like, "Well,
okay, but what did Rothko feel?"

00:19:16.560 --> 00:19:19.560
He probably wasn't feeling
anything to do with Alfred Molina

00:19:19.560 --> 00:19:24.560
or my ex-girlfriend... probably... 
But the despair,

00:19:24.750 --> 00:19:29.010
the sadness, the trappedness, yeah, maybe.

00:19:29.010 --> 00:19:30.660
I mean, he did say that
he felt those things

00:19:30.660 --> 00:19:32.100
when he wrote about the paintings.

00:19:32.100 --> 00:19:33.690
So maybe that's it.

00:19:33.690 --> 00:19:37.230
Maybe if I stand in front of
them and I feel the same thing

00:19:37.230 --> 00:19:39.240
that the artist felt when he made it,

00:19:39.240 --> 00:19:41.921
that means I've got it!
But hang on a minute,

00:19:41.921 --> 00:19:44.970
we've already tried this.

00:19:44.970 --> 00:19:45.960
Remember a minute ago,

00:19:45.960 --> 00:19:47.970
we learned about how
the artist's intention

00:19:47.970 --> 00:19:50.901
can be a tricky concept
because intentions change

00:19:50.901 --> 00:19:53.580
over time and the artists themself

00:19:53.580 --> 00:19:56.190
might be just another interpretation?

00:19:56.190 --> 00:19:58.500
How do I know I'm not doing the same thing

00:19:58.500 --> 00:20:00.840
with Rothko's feelings?

00:20:00.840 --> 00:20:03.990
In "Pale Fire", John Shade
obviously felt a lot of things,

00:20:03.990 --> 00:20:05.850
but how do we know whether or not Charles

00:20:05.850 --> 00:20:07.350
picked up on the right ones?

00:20:07.350 --> 00:20:10.470
In my play, there are
like nine characters

00:20:10.470 --> 00:20:13.590
some of whom feel things that
I've never felt in real life.

00:20:13.590 --> 00:20:17.103
So what is the audience supposed to feel?

00:20:18.106 --> 00:20:20.223
I am Pablo Picasso's paintings.

00:20:21.270 --> 00:20:24.123
How do you feel about me?

00:20:25.350 --> 00:20:27.893
[Hidden voice]
Here's an idea!

00:20:27.893 --> 00:20:29.552
Who gives a sh*t?

00:20:29.552 --> 00:20:32.135
[Music like "Whooaaa we're changing it up again!"]

00:20:34.920 --> 00:20:39.920
I am "Salvator Mundi," by
Leonardo "The Big Dog" da Vinci.

00:20:40.800 --> 00:20:44.250
In 2017, I was bought
by Saudi Arabian ruler

00:20:44.250 --> 00:20:47.740
Mohammed bin Salman for $450,312,500,

00:20:53.550 --> 00:20:56.550
which makes me, oh my gosh!

00:20:56.550 --> 00:21:00.900
I guess that makes me the
most valuable painting in the world!

00:21:00.900 --> 00:21:04.230
 in the world!

00:21:04.230 --> 00:21:08.100
or how people feel, not the
art world, that's for sure.

00:21:08.100 --> 00:21:10.370
Salvator Mundi is a portrait of Jesus,

00:21:10.370 --> 00:21:14.490
a man who famously did
not have a high opinion

00:21:14.490 --> 00:21:15.483
of rich people.

00:21:16.432 --> 00:21:20.362
[USSR National Anthem plays]

00:21:20.362 --> 00:21:22.470
But that didn't matter because art

00:21:22.470 --> 00:21:27.210
is what economists call an asset
or in poor people language,

00:21:27.210 --> 00:21:30.360
it's a way to avoid paying taxes.

00:21:30.360 --> 00:21:31.920
Let me give you some advice, okay.

00:21:31.920 --> 00:21:35.010
This is now Salvator's
business influencer tips,

00:21:35.010 --> 00:21:37.680
buy cheap paintings.

00:21:37.680 --> 00:21:38.513
And when I say cheap,

00:21:38.513 --> 00:21:41.670
I mean like rich people cheap
like $25,000, that's nothing.

00:21:41.670 --> 00:21:44.940
Take those cheap
paintings to an appraiser,

00:21:44.940 --> 00:21:47.370
one that you trust and say, "Hey Jimmy,

00:21:47.370 --> 00:21:49.230
how much would you say
this painting is worth?"

00:21:49.230 --> 00:21:53.790
And Jimmy goes, "Oh, I don't
know, maybe a million dollars."

00:21:53.790 --> 00:21:56.670
And then what you do is
donate that work of art

00:21:56.670 --> 00:21:58.560
to a charitable foundation,

00:21:58.560 --> 00:22:00.420
preferably one that you control.

00:22:00.420 --> 00:22:03.210
Oh, but Salvi, I hear you
say, why am I giving it away?

00:22:03.210 --> 00:22:04.440
Why am I not selling it?

00:22:04.440 --> 00:22:07.170
Well, because as far as the
tax collectors are concerned,

00:22:07.170 --> 00:22:10.230
you just donated a million
dollars to charity my friend,

00:22:10.230 --> 00:22:12.360
you're practically a saint!

00:22:12.360 --> 00:22:15.960
So use it for clout! And more importantly, it's a tax writeoff!

00:22:15.960 --> 00:22:19.680
Or try it this way around.

00:22:19.680 --> 00:22:21.480
Let's say you already own a painting.

00:22:21.480 --> 00:22:24.870
And it's very valuable - 
like me! But not me.

00:22:24.870 --> 00:22:28.740
Obviously, you couldn't afford me. I'm Jesus Christ Superstar!

00:22:28.740 --> 00:22:31.350
Take that valuable painting to your appraiser and say,

00:22:31.350 --> 00:22:34.110
"Hey Jimmy, how much would
you say this one is worth?"

00:22:34.110 --> 00:22:38.821
And Jimmy says, "Oh, I don't know. Not much I reckon."

00:22:38.821 --> 00:22:40.803
Then what you do is you die.

00:22:42.720 --> 00:22:45.060
The method is up to you there.

00:22:45.060 --> 00:22:48.840
But when you go, donate
that valuable painting

00:22:48.840 --> 00:22:50.430
to your spoiled rich kids,

00:22:50.430 --> 00:22:53.759
to Ferdinand and Jemima and Armancio,

00:22:53.759 --> 00:22:56.100
they then sell it.

00:22:56.100 --> 00:22:57.330
And oh, wouldn't, you know it,

00:22:57.330 --> 00:23:00.600
it's actually worth loads of money now!

00:23:00.600 --> 00:23:04.110
But by that point they've
already avoided inheritance tax.

00:23:04.110 --> 00:23:05.618
Boom.

00:23:05.618 --> 00:23:06.622
[cha-ching]

00:23:06.622 --> 00:23:10.770
You can look down proudly from heaven, 
where rich people definitely go.

00:23:10.770 --> 00:23:14.640
The art market is pretty unregulated,

00:23:14.640 --> 00:23:18.210
pretty opaque and very concentrated.

00:23:18.210 --> 00:23:22.590
And if you have the
millions it takes to buy in,

00:23:22.590 --> 00:23:27.330
there are millions of ways
you can stack the deck.

00:23:27.330 --> 00:23:29.820
Whilst the plebs are
standing in front of the work

00:23:29.820 --> 00:23:31.618
trying to figure out what it means,

00:23:31.618 --> 00:23:35.130
you already know what it means.

00:23:35.130 --> 00:23:37.860
It means you never have to work again!

00:23:37.860 --> 00:23:39.270
Huge vibe.

00:23:39.270 --> 00:23:44.270
- Except, well, it's hard
to be completely cynical.

00:23:47.010 --> 00:23:49.500
Even in the ritziest of ritzy art circles,

00:23:49.500 --> 00:23:52.380
people do still talk about the meaning.

00:23:52.380 --> 00:23:56.070
In the early noughties, a
new art movement developed,

00:23:56.070 --> 00:24:00.480
that came to be known as Zombie Formalism.

00:24:00.480 --> 00:24:03.900
Pretty quickly, people started to suspect

00:24:03.900 --> 00:24:08.900
that zombie formalism was just
trying to make a quick buck.

00:24:09.030 --> 00:24:10.830
A lot of the paintings themselves

00:24:10.830 --> 00:24:12.960
were pretty visually neutral

00:24:12.960 --> 00:24:16.620
so you could hang them in a
CEO's office or a fancy lobby

00:24:16.620 --> 00:24:20.460
and they'd take up space
without pulling too much focus.

00:24:20.460 --> 00:24:21.870
Some of them pushed boundaries,

00:24:21.870 --> 00:24:25.200
but in ways that didn't always
seem significant like, oh,

00:24:25.200 --> 00:24:26.790
it's the first painting ever to be done

00:24:26.790 --> 00:24:28.083
with a fire extinguisher.

00:24:30.540 --> 00:24:31.890
Great.

00:24:31.890 --> 00:24:33.829
And a lot of them got flipped:

00:24:33.829 --> 00:24:36.600
bought cheap first time round,

00:24:36.600 --> 00:24:40.440
sold very expensive on
the secondary market.

00:24:40.440 --> 00:24:43.890
These examples are the
"Seven Rain Paintings"

00:24:43.890 --> 00:24:45.000
by Lucien Smith,

00:24:45.000 --> 00:24:47.580
one of the most prominent
zombie formalists,

00:24:47.580 --> 00:24:49.752
and they made him very rich.

00:24:49.752 --> 00:24:52.890
When they were exhibited in LA,

00:24:52.890 --> 00:24:56.287
they were accompanied by this description.

00:24:56.287 --> 00:24:59.790
"Smith's work acts as a tangible moment,

00:24:59.790 --> 00:25:04.710
a Chronicle of exploration as
he negotiates with existence,

00:25:04.710 --> 00:25:08.607
he reminds us that an artist's trajectory is a 
[nonsense babbling]"

00:25:12.180 --> 00:25:13.013
What?

00:25:13.950 --> 00:25:16.200
I don't even remember what that said.

00:25:16.200 --> 00:25:19.080
Those words just slid off my brain.

00:25:19.080 --> 00:25:20.727
That that was pure bullsh*t.

00:25:21.870 --> 00:25:23.700
And yeah, a lot of philosophers

00:25:23.700 --> 00:25:26.550
and art critics actually
said that at the time

00:25:26.550 --> 00:25:28.830
or words to that effect.

00:25:28.830 --> 00:25:31.380
Interestingly, Lucien Smith himself

00:25:31.380 --> 00:25:34.837
has since come forward
and kindof admitted it!

00:25:34.837 --> 00:25:37.620
"The model that was set
for me when I was younger,

00:25:37.620 --> 00:25:39.540
it wasn't a healthy model.

00:25:39.540 --> 00:25:41.760
It was about sucking up to
collectors and trying to sell

00:25:41.760 --> 00:25:43.080
for the highest prices.

00:25:43.080 --> 00:25:47.610
That stuff isn't real, that's not art."

00:25:47.610 --> 00:25:48.990
According to his website,

00:25:48.990 --> 00:25:53.010
Smith is now living in
New York, making NFTs

00:25:53.010 --> 00:25:57.197
for a company called Lobus, which... 

00:25:58.560 --> 00:26:01.740
if somebody had accused
me of making worthless art

00:26:01.740 --> 00:26:03.540
just so that it could be sold to fools

00:26:03.540 --> 00:26:04.972
to make a lot of money,

00:26:04.972 --> 00:26:08.910
I probably wouldn't get into crypto, man.

00:26:08.910 --> 00:26:12.090
But even at its most cynical,

00:26:12.090 --> 00:26:16.230
people still had to act
like the art had meaning.

00:26:16.230 --> 00:26:19.350
Part of the process of building
hype around a new artist

00:26:19.350 --> 00:26:20.850
is convincing people that their work

00:26:20.850 --> 00:26:22.710
has something interesting to say.

00:26:22.710 --> 00:26:25.510
And zombie formalism didn't last in part

00:26:25.510 --> 00:26:29.430
because audiences and
critics saw through it.

00:26:29.430 --> 00:26:30.960
Other trends took its place,

00:26:30.960 --> 00:26:33.690
including a trend for what
you might call woke art

00:26:33.690 --> 00:26:37.230
or art with social and political meaning.

00:26:37.230 --> 00:26:40.856
Yes, it's a financial asset,
but people still want to stand

00:26:40.856 --> 00:26:44.673
in front of a painting
and feel like they get it.

00:26:45.750 --> 00:26:48.693
And I still do, with Rothko.

00:26:50.527 --> 00:27:03.677
[chill synth music like "Hmmm, thoughtful."

00:27:04.855 --> 00:27:08.160
It's tricky because there is
kindof a cultural pressure

00:27:08.160 --> 00:27:12.570
with art, especially modern
art, to act like you get it.

00:27:12.570 --> 00:27:14.040
And I know that there are some people

00:27:14.040 --> 00:27:15.480
who respond to that pressure

00:27:15.480 --> 00:27:17.880
by just denying that modern
art can have meaning.

00:27:17.880 --> 00:27:19.620
They're like, "Oh, nobody really gets it.

00:27:19.620 --> 00:27:21.750
Nobody really likes it,
they just pretend to!"

00:27:21.750 --> 00:27:24.570
and that's always seemed
kindof cynical to me.

00:27:24.570 --> 00:27:26.850
But at the same time, I
do feel that pressure.

00:27:26.850 --> 00:27:30.870
Like I feel like I should have
opinions about Mark Rothko.

00:27:30.870 --> 00:27:33.690
I should be that kind of cultured person.

00:27:33.690 --> 00:27:35.763
But I guess if that's
how I'm approaching it,

00:27:35.763 --> 00:27:38.250
then I'm not really engaging with the art.

00:27:38.250 --> 00:27:40.110
I'm just worried about the kind of person

00:27:40.110 --> 00:27:42.240
that I feel I should be.

00:27:42.240 --> 00:27:44.520
Like, "Oh, what if I get invited to a party

00:27:44.520 --> 00:27:46.140
and I say the wrong
thing about Mark Rothko

00:27:46.140 --> 00:27:48.030
and I make a fool of myself?"

00:27:48.030 --> 00:27:49.860
But that's a silly way to approach it.

00:27:49.860 --> 00:27:51.870
Because even if I got everything

00:27:51.870 --> 00:27:53.755
there was to get about Rothko,

00:27:53.755 --> 00:27:56.550
there's thousands of other artists here

00:27:56.550 --> 00:27:59.550
that would confront me
with that same anxiety.

00:27:59.550 --> 00:28:01.680
If you come to art looking for a stick

00:28:01.680 --> 00:28:04.740
to beat yourself with, then
you're probably gonna find it.

00:28:04.740 --> 00:28:06.544
So maybe we should ask
a different question,

00:28:06.544 --> 00:28:11.544
which is, what is the
point of trying to get it?

00:28:17.340 --> 00:28:20.790
When I was a child, we studied "Macbeth"

00:28:20.790 --> 00:28:22.380
in English class.

00:28:22.380 --> 00:28:23.220
If you don't know it,

00:28:23.220 --> 00:28:27.120
it's about a guy who murders
the king and steals the throne.

00:28:27.120 --> 00:28:31.590
And there's a running theme
in the play about clothing.

00:28:31.590 --> 00:28:32.790
People say that Macbeth

00:28:32.790 --> 00:28:34.979
is wearing somebody else's clothes

00:28:34.979 --> 00:28:38.670
as a metaphor for him stealing the crown.

00:28:38.670 --> 00:28:41.430
They say that his new
title doesn't fit him.

00:28:41.430 --> 00:28:46.260
"It hangs loose about him like a giant's robe 
upon a dwarfish thief."

00:28:46.260 --> 00:28:48.630
Macbeth is all about the drip.

00:28:48.630 --> 00:28:50.940
and I, being a little wise ass,

00:28:50.940 --> 00:28:54.750
put up my hand and said,
"Miss, did Shakespeare

00:28:54.750 --> 00:28:57.960
really intend to put that in there?"

00:28:57.960 --> 00:29:01.740
And there's two ways of
asking that question.

00:29:01.740 --> 00:29:04.650
The first is, did the actual man,

00:29:04.650 --> 00:29:07.830
William Shakespeare,
actually sit down in 1606

00:29:07.830 --> 00:29:09.600
and have the thought,

00:29:09.600 --> 00:29:13.143
"I am going to use a clothing
metaphor in my new play.

00:29:15.150 --> 00:29:18.090
And then I'm gonna send a bunch
of flirty sonnets to someone

00:29:18.090 --> 00:29:20.720
and make them wonder whether I'm bisexual."

00:29:20.720 --> 00:29:24.400
[Saint Motel's "Just My Type" plays]

00:29:24.450 --> 00:29:26.520
There's no way we can know
whether he thought that

00:29:26.520 --> 00:29:28.860
without a time machine and a mind reader.

00:29:28.860 --> 00:29:32.100
But the second way of
asking the question is,

00:29:32.100 --> 00:29:34.397
do we get more out of the play

00:29:34.397 --> 00:29:39.397
if we assume that the
clothing metaphor is intended,

00:29:39.840 --> 00:29:41.280
do we enjoy it more?

00:29:41.280 --> 00:29:43.693
Does it prompt us to some
interesting reflections

00:29:43.693 --> 00:29:47.970
if we assume that we
are meant to notice it?

00:29:47.970 --> 00:29:50.550
if we just go, nah,
that's just a coincidence.

00:29:50.550 --> 00:29:51.720
Don't worry about it.

00:29:51.720 --> 00:29:53.640
Then are we missing out?

00:29:53.640 --> 00:29:55.410
The philosopher Alan Goldman

00:29:55.410 --> 00:29:57.296
says that the point of interpreting art

00:29:57.296 --> 00:30:02.296
 is to maximise its artistic value.

00:30:02.550 --> 00:30:05.160
Now what exactly is artistic value?

00:30:05.160 --> 00:30:07.363
Well, maybe that's another
story for another time,

00:30:07.363 --> 00:30:12.363
but his point is that getting
it is not a competition.

00:30:12.660 --> 00:30:14.580
It's not about being right.

00:30:14.580 --> 00:30:16.440
But then how do we know that Charles

00:30:16.440 --> 00:30:18.845
is wrong about "Pale Fire"?

00:30:18.845 --> 00:30:23.043
Because if he's right
then the poem isn't good.

00:30:23.940 --> 00:30:26.550
John Shade leaves behind
this amazing work.

00:30:26.550 --> 00:30:29.730
He writes about being an old
man at the end of his life

00:30:29.730 --> 00:30:32.220
and what it was like to lose his daughter

00:30:32.220 --> 00:30:35.250
and it's really, really moving.

00:30:35.250 --> 00:30:37.590
If we assume, as Charles does, that, oh,

00:30:37.590 --> 00:30:39.970
that stuff doesn't matter,
it's really all about him,

00:30:39.970 --> 00:30:43.533
well then it's kind of a waste.

00:30:44.550 --> 00:30:47.610
That's what makes Charles
a tragic character.

00:30:47.610 --> 00:30:51.930
He's so lost in his own
mess that he can't see

00:30:51.930 --> 00:30:55.410
the true value of what John has made.

00:30:55.410 --> 00:31:00.240
As for me and Rothko, I
can try to put together

00:31:00.240 --> 00:31:02.700
all the different ideas
that we've looked at today.

00:31:02.700 --> 00:31:04.740
I can bear in mind what Susan Sontag said

00:31:04.740 --> 00:31:07.380
about not intellectualising
things too much.

00:31:07.380 --> 00:31:10.620
I can remember that the process
by which art gets exhibited

00:31:10.620 --> 00:31:13.050
is often a financial thing
rather than an arbiter

00:31:13.050 --> 00:31:16.380
of its meaning, so I don't
have to feel pressured by that.

00:31:16.380 --> 00:31:19.380
And I can also try to think
about what Rothko himself

00:31:19.380 --> 00:31:20.610
might have intended or felt,

00:31:20.610 --> 00:31:22.375
not so I can reconstruct his brain,

00:31:22.375 --> 00:31:27.360
but so I can see whether I
can also feel those things.

00:31:27.360 --> 00:31:30.153
I'm looking for new experiences
when I go to his art,

00:31:31.022 --> 00:31:33.099
I'm trying to grow and develop

00:31:33.099 --> 00:31:37.233
as a person, rather than trying to get it.

00:31:38.340 --> 00:31:40.971
As I've been writing my play,

00:31:40.971 --> 00:31:43.769
I've had to deal with a
lot of these questions

